  temp = temp // 10    return count# Read input and execute the functionL, R, X = map(int, input().split())print(countX(L, R, X))\`\`\` Explanation1. Reading Input: The input values for ( L ), ( R ), and ( X ) are read from standard input.2. Iterate Through Range: For each number ( n ) in the range ( [L+1, R-1] ):   - Check Each Digit: Convert the number into its individual digits using modulo 10 (to get the last digit) and integer division by 10 (to remove the last digit).   - Count Matches: Each digit is compared with ( X ), and if they match, the count is incremented.3. Output Result: The accumulated count is printed as the result.This approach ensures that each number in the specified range is checked efficiently, and each digit is examined individually. The time complexity is ( O((R-L) cdot log R) ), which is efficient given the problem constraints."},{"problem":"Edward Elric is chasing after Scar. To stop Edward, Scar creates N barriers in the way, numbered from 1 to N. Each barrier Scar created is either one of the following two types.Type 1 barrier - This barrier starts from a height X above the ground and extends till the sky.Type 2 barrier - This barrier starts from the ground and extends up to height X above the ground.The height of Edward is H units and he has an alchemic life force of L units. Moreover, he can duck by Y_{1} units and jump by height Y_{2} units (as explained in the figures). He starts crossing barriers in sequence, starting from barrier 1 till the barrier N. Whenever he can't pass a barrier by ducking or jumping (considered passed even when the barrier just touches him), he uses Alchemy to break the barrier. However, this costs him a single unit of his alchemic life force.If after breaking a barrier no life force is left, Edward gets completely exhausted, unable to pass that barrier.   How many barriers can Edward cross?   And remember never to call him a pipsqueak if his height is too short!------  Input: ------The first line contains T